metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #222
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Sixty# #163
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Miniscapes #257
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Teleport Loopr #38
metadata.description:
Video-art loop randomly generated by a p5.js code ~

_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _

Assuming that teleports would rearrange the experience of time, how would time feel like if you were trapped into teleport loops?

This is a project about time

, space

, displacement

, deterritorialization

, abstraction

, reterritorialization

, inversion?

A dream looper, a teleport machine.

_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _

There were 30 .mp4 files available to be randomly chosen.

All videos take part on my audiovisual research and were recorded between 2016 and 2021 in Brasil, Chile and Canary Islands. They're all short and looped in this project, just like moving photos.

Videos per iteration could be:

[3], [4] or [5]

Color inversion effect could have been applied to:

[one video], [none (rare)] or [variable (super rare)]

_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _

by Filipe Britto

@fitipeArt (twitter)

@fitipe (ig)

metadata.name: Sap song #98
metadata.description:
This audiovisual generative artwork proposes sonorous green forms that flow excessively. Frenetic arpeggios and populations of plants are emerging, organized in their own way. And the sap sings, feeds and shows us a constructive desire for afforestation.

The work has 3 moments:
I. “Enredo coral”
II. “Recitativo libre”
III. “Coda hacia la raíz”

Original cello, marimba and music box samplers.

[s] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)

attributes.value: Diurnal organic green version, in exotic A minor mode, for choir of 50 voices/plants.

metadata.name: Mur #201
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: overloaded #368
metadata.description: Overloaded attempts to be a system to explore time perception, through non-representative images, while still representing pixels as upscaled forms. It plays with permanence and non-permanence.

metadata.name: Reading a book #429
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.
